0 received, 100% loss.\n\n5. Routing/FIB on leaf_router_0_0 (critical evidence)\n   - ip -d route and show ip route on leaf_router_0_0 show:\n     - A kernel route (K) entry: \"K * 10.0.0.0/24 [0/0] unreachable (blackhole)\"\n     - Also present: \"C>* 10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, eth2\"\n     - ip -d route lists \"blackhole 10.0.0.0/24 proto boot scope global\" before the local entries.\n   - In short: leaf_router_0_0 has a blackhole/unreachable route for its own LAN prefix 10.0.0.0/24 installed in the kernel/RIB and that blackhole is taking effect.\n\nAnalysis / localization\n- Because BGP is advertising both /24s correctly and next-hops across spines and super-spine appear consistent, the control plane is not the immediate problem.\n- Packets from pc_0_1 follow the normal path to leaf_router_0_0 (through spine), but when leaf_router_0_0 receives packets for 10.0.0.0/24 they are matched by the kernel blackhole/unreachable route and dropped instead of being delivered out eth2 to pc_0_0.\n- The presence of both a blackhole (K) route and a connected (C) route for the same prefix on leaf_router_0_0 indicates the forwarding plane is configured/installed incorrectly for that prefix on that router. This is the direct cause of the observed end-to-end connectivity failure.\n\nRoot cause\n- A blackhole/unreachable kernel route for 10.0.0.0/24 exists on leaf_router_0_0 and is taking precedence in the FIB, causing packets destined to the 10.0.0.0/24 network to be dropped instead of forwarded to the local interface (eth2). This misinstalled/unexpected kernel route is the root cause of host-to-host connectivity failure.\n\nImpact\n- pc_0_0 is unreachable from other hosts (pc_0_1 and leaf_router_0_1/spines), and traffic destined for 10.0.0.0/24 arriving at leaf_router_0_0 will be dropped.\n- BGP control-plane visibility remains intact — other routers believe they can reach the 10.0.0.0/24 network and forward traffic toward leaf_router_0_0, but the forwarding plane on leaf_router_0_0 prevents delivery.\n\nEvidence (representative lines)\n- Reachability: pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: 100% loss\n- leaf_router_0_0 show ip route:\n  - \"K * 10.0.0.0/24 [0/0] unreachable (blackhole)\"\n  - \"C>* 10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, eth2\"\n- leaf_router_0_0 ip -d route:\n  - \"blackhole 10.0.0.0/24 proto boot scope global\"\n  - local 10.0.0.1 dev eth2 table local ...\n\nConfidence\n- High: the blackhole/unreachable route on leaf_router_0_0 is directly observable in the kernel route table and explains the exact symptom (packets dropped for 10.0.0.0/24). BGP and interface states corroborate that forwarding on that router is the broken piece.\n\nNotes (no remediation included)\n- The report deliberately does not propose remediation steps (per request). If you want, I can next (on request) identify the likely configuration command or FRR behavior that installed the blackhole route and show exact configuration outputs (FRR running-config) to further pinpoint the misconfiguration.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 12086, "output_tokens": 3053, "total_tokens": 15139, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 11776}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1600}}}
